04920nam a22005775i 9780822387879DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223878797 a10.1515/97808223878792doi  a(DE-B1597)553458  a(OCoLC)1055302400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC327b.O54 2006 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a323.6012221 aOng, Aihwa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeoliberalism as Exception :bMutations in Citizenship and Sovereignty /cAihwa Ong. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b6 b&w photos, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Neoliberalism as Exception, Exception to Neoliberalism -- tI. Ethics in Contention -- t1. Sisterly Solidarity: Feminist Virtue under ''Moderate Islam'' -- t2. Cyberpublics and the Pitfalls of Diasporic Chinese Politics -- tII. Spaces of Governing -- t3. Graduated Sovereignty -- t4. Zoning Technologies in East Asia -- tIII. Circuits of Expertise -- t5. Latitudes, or How Markets Stretch the Bounds of Governmentality -- t6. Higher Learning in Global Space -- t7. Labor Arbitrage: Displacements and Betrayals in Silicon Valley -- tIV. The Edge of Emergence -- t8. Baroque Ecology, E√ervescent Citizenship -- t9. A Biocartography: Maids, Neoslavery, and ngos -- t10. Reengineering the ''Chinese Soul'' in Shanghai? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNeoliberalism is commonly viewed as an economic doctrine that seeks to limit the scope of government. Some consider it a form of predatory capitalism with adverse effects on the Global South. In this groundbreaking work, Aihwa Ong offers an alternative view of neoliberalism as an extraordinarily malleable technology of governing that is taken up in different ways by different regimes, be they authoritarian, democratic, or communist. Ong shows how East and Southeast Asian states are making exceptions to their usual practices of governing in order to position themselves to compete in the global economy. As she demonstrates, a variety of neoliberal strategies of governing are re-engineering political spaces and populations. Ong's ethnographic case studies illuminate experiments and developments such as China's creation of special market zones within its socialist economy; pro-capitalist Islam and women's rights in Malaysia; Singapore's repositioning as a hub of scientific expertise; and flexible labor and knowledge regimes that span the Pacific.Ong traces how these and other neoliberal exceptions to business as usual are reconfiguring relationships between governing and the governed, power and knowledge, and sovereignty and territoriality. She argues that an interactive mode of citizenship is emerging, one that organizes people-and distributes rights and benefits to them-according to their marketable skills rather than according to their membership within nation-states. Those whose knowledge and skills are not assigned significant market value-such as migrant women working as domestic maids in many Asian cities-are denied citizenship. Nevertheless, Ong suggests that as the seam between sovereignty and citizenship is pried apart, a new space is emerging for NGOs to advocate for the human rights of those excluded by neoliberal measures of human worthiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAutonomy. 0aCitizenship. 0aCulture and globalizationzChina. 0aSelf-determination, National. 0aState, The. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978